'''Nagibayashi Shrine''' (名木林神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|de|Shintoschrein|ja|神社|zh|神社}} located in {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|de|Gifu-Präfektur|ja|岐阜県|zh|岐阜县}}, {{ill|Anpachi District|de|Kreis Anpachi|ja|安八郡|zh|安八郡}}, {{ill|Anpachi|de|Anpachi|ja|安八町|zh|安八町}}.

It is one of the claimants to the title of the Iku-ragawamiya of {{ill|Moto-Ise|de|Moto-Ise|ja|元伊勢|zh|元伊势}} in {{ill|Mino Province|de|Provinz Mino|ja|美濃国|zh|美浓国}}, and its former shrine rank was Gōsha. Alternative names include Shinmei Shrine and Fuji ShrineNamed for an ancient {{ill|wisteria|de|Glyzinie|ja|藤|zh|紫藤}} in the former precincts..

According to one theory, this shrine gave its name to the local area of {{ill|Ōmori Village (Anpachi District, Gifu)|de|Dorf Ōmori (Kreis Anpachi, Gifu)|ja|大森村 (岐阜県安八郡)|zh|大森村 (岐阜县安八郡)|lt=Ōmori|lt_ja=大森|lt_de=Ōmori|lt_zh=大森}}, and later to {{ill|Namori Village|de|Namori-Dorf|ja|名森村|zh|名森村}}.The characters for "tree" and "forest" were combined to form "forest" (森).

== History and Overview ==

The founding date is unknown. In the Heian period's shrine register of Mino Province it is listed as "Shōgoi Nagibayashi Myōjin." The name "Nagibayashi" was once pronounced "Nagihaya."

In {{ill|1872|de|1872|ja|1872年|zh|1872年}} (Meiji 5), it was designated as a Gōsha.

On {{ill|1934|de|1934|ja|1934年|zh|1934年}} (Shōwa 9) August 30, due to riverbed changes from construction on the upper {{ill|Kiso River|de|Kiso-Fluss|ja|木曽川|zh|木曾川}}, the shrine was moved from its former location (then Ōmori, Namori Village, Anpachi District) to its present site.

