'''Nagibayashi Shrine''' (名木林神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Gifu Prefecture|Gifu Prefecture]], [[:en:Anpachi District, Gifu|Anpachi District]], [[:en:Anpachi, Gifu|Anpachi]].

It is one of the claimants to the title of the Iku-ragawamiya of {{ill|Moto-Ise|de|Moto-Ise|ja|元伊勢|zh|元伊势|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moto-Ise|qq=}} in [[:en:Mino Province|Mino Province]], and its former shrine rank was Gōsha. Alternative names include Shinmei Shrine and Fuji ShrineNamed for an ancient {{ill|wisteria|de|Glyzinie|ja|藤|zh|紫藤|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wisteria|qq=}} in the former precincts..

According to one theory, this shrine gave its name to the local area of {{ill|Ōmori Village (Anpachi District, Gifu)|de|Dorf Ōmori (Kreis Anpachi, Gifu)|ja|大森村 (岐阜県安八郡)|zh|大森村 (岐阜县安八郡)|lt=Ōmori|lt_ja=大森|lt_de=Ōmori|lt_zh=大森|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmori Village (Anpachi District, Gifu)|qq=}}, and later to {{ill|Namori Village|de|Namori-Dorf|ja|名森村|zh|名森村|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Namori Village|qq=}}.The characters for "tree" and "forest" were combined to form "forest" (森).

== History and Overview ==

The founding date is unknown. In the Heian period's shrine register of Mino Province it is listed as "Shōgoi Nagibayashi Myōjin." The name "Nagibayashi" was once pronounced "Nagihaya."

In [[:en:1872|1872]] (Meiji 5), it was designated as a Gōsha.

On [[:en:1934|1934]] (Shōwa 9) August 30, due to riverbed changes from construction on the upper [[:en:Kiso River|Kiso River]], the shrine was moved from its former location (then Ōmori, Namori Village, Anpachi District) to its present site.

